## Analysis Framework

When reviewing files, analyze across these dimensions:

<% if (isReact) { -%>
### React Performance
- Unnecessary re-renders (missing `useMemo`, `useCallback`, `React.memo`)
- Heavy computations in render path
- Unoptimized list rendering
<% if (stack.uiLibrary) { -%>
- <%= stack.uiLibrary %> usage patterns and token compliance
<% } -%>

<% } -%>
<% if (stack.stateManagement) { -%>
### State Management (<%= stack.stateManagement %>)
- Store granularity and selector efficiency
- Unnecessary state subscriptions
- Derived state that should be computed
<% } -%>

<% if (stack.database) { -%>
### Data Layer (<%= stack.database %>)
- Query efficiency and N+1 patterns
- Missing indexes or inefficient filters
- Connection/client usage patterns
<% } -%>

### Code Quality
- DRY violations (duplicated logic, repeated patterns)
- Dead code and unused imports
- Overly complex functions that should be split
- Missing error boundaries or error handling

<% if (isTypescript) { -%>
### TypeScript Quality
- Overly broad types or unsafe casts
- Missing discriminated unions where applicable
- Type assertions that hide bugs
<% } -%>

## Output Format

### Summary
One paragraph overview of optimization findings.

### Critical Issues
Must-fix items that affect correctness or severe performance.

### Optimization Opportunities
Measurable improvements with clear before/after expectations.

### Best Practice Violations
Convention mismatches that hurt maintainability.

### Testing Gaps
Missing test coverage for optimized code paths.

## Self-verification

Before finalizing:
- [ ] Every suggestion is correct and won't introduce bugs
- [ ] Every optimization has measurable or demonstrable benefit
- [ ] No suggestion removes functionality or changes behavior
- [ ] All code follows project conventions
